  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Resurface options.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pebble (Pebblecrete, Quartzon Original, Diamond Brite):</strong> Aggregate-and-cement matrix. Textured grippy surface. 12&ndash;18 year next-life on Gold Coast salt pool. ~$9K&ndash;$14K for an 8m pool. Default choice for pebble-on-pebble replacement.</li>
          <li><strong>Quartzon Quartz / Diamond Brite Quartz:</strong> Quartz aggregate matrix, smoother and more durable than pebble. 18&ndash;25 year lifespan. Less heel-rough on bare feet. ~$12K&ndash;$18K for an 8m pool. The 2026-standard upgrade choice.</li>
          <li><strong>Full mosaic glass / ceramic tile:</strong> Tile the entire interior with 25&times;25mm glass or ceramic mosaic. 30+ year lifespan if grout is maintained. Premium look. ~$25K&ndash;$55K for an 8m pool. Common on Burleigh Hill / canal-estate rebuilds.</li>
          <li><strong>Mineral surface (Bisazza-style hybrid):</strong> Newer composite finish, between quartz and tile. Smooth, refined look. ~$18K&ndash;$28K.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Signs your pool needs resurfacing now.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sandpaper-rough surface.</strong> Scrapes your feet when you walk on the floor. Aggregate matrix is breaking down.</li>
          <li><strong>Visible aggregate &ldquo;plucking&rdquo;.</strong> Small pin-holes where individual stones have popped out. Accelerates rapidly once it starts.</li>
          <li><strong>Rust streaks that won&rsquo;t acid-wash off.</strong> Rebar corrosion bleeding through pinholes. The shell is no longer waterproof at those points.</li>
          <li><strong>Dark grey / beige patches.</strong> pH chemistry has fried the surface (usually from incorrect chlorinator setpoint over years).</li>
          <li><strong>Surface no longer holds chemistry.</strong> You add chlorine and it&rsquo;s gone in 2 days &mdash; usually because the surface is absorbing it.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebar visible.</strong> URGENT. The concrete shell is spalling. Resurface NOW or risk full structural failure.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The resurface process &mdash; what we actually do.</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Drain pool. Pump-out water (water-cart or sewer-trade waste).</li>
          <li><strong>Day 2&ndash;3:</strong> Hand-chip + jackhammer the existing surface off. Roughen to expose sound concrete substrate.</li>
          <li><strong>Day 4:</strong> Acid wash + bond-coat application. Check for any deeper structural issues (cracks, rebar exposure).</li>
          <li><strong>Day 5&ndash;7:</strong> Apply new interior. Pebble: trowel + spray application. Quartz: similar. Tile: lay mosaic sheets in a thin-set mortar.</li>
          <li><strong>Day 8&ndash;10:</strong> Cure. Grout (if tile). Acid wash final surface.</li>
          <li><strong>Day 11&ndash;14:</strong> Fill, balance chemistry, commission equipment, run for 7 days before final handover.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Common &ldquo;while we&rsquo;re here&rdquo; add-ons.</h3>
        <p>
          About 70% of resurface projects include at least one of these &mdash;
          and bundling saves 15&ndash;25% vs doing them separately:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>New coping (travertine, bluestone, or matching pool surround stone) ~$3K&ndash;$8K</li>
          <li>Equipment modernisation (variable-speed pump, new chlorinator, heating) ~$4K&ndash;$9K</li>
          <li>New paving around pool ~$5K&ndash;$20K</li>
          <li>New glass fence to bring up to current Form 23 compliance ~$4K&ndash;$12K</li>
          <li>LED lighting retrofit ~$1.5K&ndash;$3K</li>
          <li>Salt cell + chlorinator replacement ~$1.5K&ndash;$3K</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Structural assessment first.</h3>
        <p>
          Before we quote a resurface we look hard at the underlying shell. If
          the concrete has spalled badly, the rebar is going, or there&rsquo;s a
          significant crack network, resurface is throwing money at a problem
          that&rsquo;s coming back. We&rsquo;ll tell you honestly &mdash; sometimes
          rebuild ($80K&ndash;$120K) is cheaper than three more resurface
          cycles. About 5&ndash;10% of pre-quote assessments end with us
          recommending replacement rather than resurface.
        </p>
